Wash and dry produce. Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{6%ounce} on a diagonal into 1⁄2-inch-thick pieces. Halve, peel, and cut @onion{1} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges. Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut crosswise into 1⁄2-inch-thick half-moons.

Heat a large drizzle of @oil{1%drizzle} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add carrots, onion, and zucchini; season with @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, half the @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}, @salt{1%pinch}, and @pepper{1%pinch}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies are softened and lightly browned, ~{7-10%minutes}.

Add @crushed tomatoes{1}, @Vidalia onion paste{1/2%ounce}, @water{1/4%cup}, and @sugar{1/2%tsp}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce has slightly thickened, ~{2-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a small #pot over medium heat. Add @precooked polenta{1} and @water{1/3%cup}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until mostly smooth, ~{30-60%seconds}.

Whisk in @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon}, @cream cheese{2%tablespoon}, @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}, and @butter{1%TBSP}; cook, whisking occasionally, until thickened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired. (If polenta seems too thick, add water 1 TBSP at a time until it reaches desired consistency.)

Meanwhile, halve and toast @ciabatta bread{1}.

Cut ciabatta on a diagonal into triangles and drizzle with @olive oil{1%drizzle}.

Divide polenta and ragù between shallow #bowls{} in separate sections. Serve ciabatta on the side.

Serve with @salmon{10%ounce} as desired.

> Fish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.